, England":"Belvoir Castle, Leicestershire, England","Evesham, Worcestershire, England":"Evesham, Worcestershire, England"},"nl":{"about 1009–1088":"circa 1009–1088","0996–1038":"0996–1038","1030–1088":"1030–1088","1009–1088":"1009–1088","0996":"0996","1038":"1038","1016":"1016","about 1009":"circa 1009","From 1030 to 1036":"van 1030 to 1036","1035":"1035","1013":"1013","1088":"1088","1066":"1066","1086":"1086","1030":"1030","1009":"1009","England":"England","Belvoir Castle, Leicestershire, England":"Belvoir Castle, Leicestershire, England","Evesham, Worcestershire, England":"Evesham, Worcestershire, England"},"en":{"about 1009–1088":"about 1009–1088","0996–1038":"0996–1038","1030–1088":"1030–1088","1009–1088":"1009–1088","0996":"0996","1038":"1038","1016":"1016","about 1009":"about 1009","From 1030 to 1036":"from 1030 to 1036","1035":"1035","1013":"1013","1088":"1088","1066":"1066","1086":"1086","1030":"1030","1009":"1009","England":"England","Belvoir Castle, Leicestershire, England":"Belvoir Castle, Leicestershire, England","Evesham, Worcestershire, England":"Evesham, Worcestershire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Osule","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Gloucestershire): of Norman origin, a variant of   Soul  .","French (<b>Soulé</b>): topographic name for someone who lived in a house exposed to sun, a variant of   Soulier   2; or a habitational name from Soulé, the name of several places in the southwestern part of France.","History: George Soule (1600–80), one of the passengers on the <i>Mayflower</i> in 1620, was one of the founders of Duxbury, MA, where he became comparatively wealthy. He left eight children."],"variants":[{"name":"Sowle","meanings":["English: variant of   Soule  . This form of the surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Soul","meanings":["English and Scottish (of Norman origin): habitational name from Soules near Saint-Lô (Manche, France).","French (mainly Manche): variant of <b>Saoul</b>, a nickname from <i>saoul</i> ‘full, satiated; drunk’, figuratively also ‘surfeited with something’.","History: The Scottish family of this name traces the name back to Ranulf de Soulis (died before 1170), a Norman knight who came to Scotland with King David I and served as his cupbearer. Sir John Soulis (died before 1310) was appointed ‘guardian of Scotland’ by John Balliol in 1301."]},{"name":"Soules","meanings":["English: variant of   Soule  .","French (<b>Soulès</b>): plural form of <b>Soulé</b> (see   Soule  )."]},{"name":"Sowl","meanings":["English: variant of   Soule  ."]}]},{"name":"Adèle","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From French  <b>Adèle</b> , an ancient name popular in medieval Europe because of the fame of a 7th-century saint, a daughter of the Frankish king Dagobert II. It is of Germanic origin, from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ (a short form of a two-element name such as <i>Adelheid</i>;  see  Adelaide  ). It was the name of William the Conqueror's youngest daughter (  <i>c.</i>1062–1137 ), who became the wife of Stephen of Blois. However, it died out in England in the later Middle Ages. It was revived in the 19th century, being the name of a character in  Johann Strauss's  opera Die Fledermaus. Its popularity was further reinforced in the 1930s as the name of a character in the novels of  Dornford Yates ."],"variants":[{"name":"Adel","meanings":["From French  <b>Adèle</b> , an ancient name popular in medieval Europe because of the fame of a 7th-century saint, a daughter of the Frankish king Dagobert II. It is of Germanic origin, from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ (a short form of a two-element name such as <i>Adelheid</i>;  see  Adelaide  ). It was the name of William the Conqueror's youngest daughter (  <i>c.</i>1062–1137 ), who became the wife of Stephen of Blois. However, it died out in England in the later Middle Ages. It was revived in the 19th century, being the name of a character in  Johann Strauss's  opera Die Fledermaus. Its popularity was further reinforced in the 1930s as the name of a character in the novels of  Dornford Yates ."]},{"name":"Adelle","meanings":["From French  <b>Adèle</b> , an ancient name popular in medieval Europe because of the fame of a 7th-century saint, a daughter of the Frankish king Dagobert II. It is of Germanic origin, from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ (a short form of a two-element name such as <i>Adelheid</i>;  see  Adelaide  ). It was the name of William the Conqueror's youngest daughter (  <i>c.</i>1062–1137 ), who became the wife of Stephen of Blois. However, it died out in England in the later Middle Ages. It was revived in the 19th century, being the name of a character in  Johann Strauss's  opera Die Fledermaus. Its popularity was further reinforced in the 1930s as the name of a character in the novels of  Dornford Yates ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705179,"age":4,"year":"1013","julianDay":2091051,"title":"Sweyn Forkbeard","description":"The Danes raided and captured England. Sweyn, King of Danes, was declared King of England on Christmas Day.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sweyn_Forkbeard","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Sweyn Forkbeard","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705180,"age":7,"year":"1016","julianDay":2092146,"title":"Canut the Great","description":"As Aethelred, King of England died, his son, Edmund Ironside devised a truce with Danish King Canute. The truce divided the kingdom between the two but Edmund died shortly after and became King of England. Several years later, he also became king of Denmark.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cnut_the_Great","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Cnut the Great","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705181,"age":26,"year":"1035","julianDay":2099086,"title":"England Divided","description":"King Canute died in 1035 and England was divided between his three sons. His son Sweyn received Norway, Harthacanute received Denmark, and Harold Harefoot received North England.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705182,"age":57,"year":"1066","julianDay":2110409,"title":"Battle of Hastings","description":"Battle of Hastings was fought between the Norman-French army and the battle-wary English army on October 14, 1066. Duke William of Normandy believed he was the rightful king rather than Harold, who had been crowned king several months earlier. Harold was killed in battle and William was crowned king on Christmas Day 1066.","url":"https://www.english-heritage.org.uk/learn/1066-and-the-norman-conquest/what-happened-battle-hastings/","urlTitle":"English Heritage - Battle of Hastings","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705183,"age":77,"year":"1086","julianDay":2117714,"title":"Domesday Book","description":"Domesday Book is Britain's earliest extant public record with information containing land surveys and landholdings commissioned by William I. The book was completed in 1086.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/domesday/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Domesday","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Adèle Osule was born about 1009, in England. She had at least 1 son with Robert de Tosny I of Belvoir. She died in Belvoir Castle, Leicestershire, England, and was buried in Evesham, Worcestershire, England."},"et":{"about 1009–1088":"umbes 1009–1088","0996–1038":"0996–1038","1030–1088":"1030–1088","1009–1088":"1009–1088","0996":"0996","1038":"1038","1016":"1016","about 1009":"umbes 1009","From 1030 to 1036":"1030 kuni 1036","1035":"1035","1013":"1013","1088":"1088","1066":"1066","1086":"1086","1030":"1030","1009":"1009","England":"England","Belvoir Castle, Leicestershire, England":"Belvoir Castle, Leicestershire, England","Evesham, Worcestershire, England":"Evesham, Worcestershire, England"},"fi":{"about 1009–1088":"noin 1009–1088","0996–1038":"0996–1038","1030–1088":"1030–1088","1009–1088":"1009–1088","0996":"0996","1038":"1038","1016":"1016","about 1009":"noin 1009","From 1030 to 1036":"vuodesta 1030 vuoteen 10